### User:
How do you align a row of divs to the right using flex in css?  Show me an example.

### Response:


Sure, here's an example of how to align a row of divs to the right using CSS flexbox:

```css
/* Define the width and height of each div */
div {
 width: 200px;
 height: 30px;
 border: 1px solid black;
}

.left-aligning-row {
 display: flex;
 flex-direction: column; /* Set the direction to row */
 justify-content: space-between; /* Align the divs with a small margin between them */
}

/* Add some content to each div */
<div class="left-aligning-row">
 <div>This text should be aligned to the right</div>
 <div>Another text should also be aligned to the right</div>
</div>
```

In this example, we define a row of `div` elements with specific width and height values. We then add a class called "left-aligning-row" to these divs, which sets them up using CSS flexbox. The direction is set to row, and the justify-content property is used to space the divs apart from each other. Finally, we add some content to each div using the `div` element.
